04524nam a22005055i 9780773563100DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735631007 a10.1515/97807735631002doi  a(DE-B1597)657456  a(OCoLC)1394872782  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD9685.C4bO5744 1992eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a333.79/321 aFleming, Keith R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPower at Cost :bOntario Hydro and Rural Electrification, 1911-1958 /cKeith R. Fleming. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tLaying the Foundations -- tRural Power Districts and the Municipal Connection -- tThe Uniform Rate and Rural Bonuses -- tConsolidating the Rural Network -- tThe Battle for the Bruce -- tRemnants of Discontent and Political Plums -- tResponses to the Depression -- tThe Rural System during the Second World War -- tSarnia and the Uniform Rate Revisited -- tThe Five Year Plan -- tConclusion -- tPremiers of Ontario, 1905-1985 -- tOfficials of the HEPC, 1906-1974 -- tRate Classifications for Rural Customers, 1909-1970 -- tStatistical Summary of the Rural System in Southern Ontario, 1912-1971 -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHydro responded to demands from residents of farms and hamlets for a fair share of the "public power" that was being distributed to municipalities in southwestern Ontario in 1910. It extended its transmission lines along the back concessions of the region, developed new agrarian applications for electricity, and devised a rural rate schedule capable of attracting new customers and encouraging electrical consumption. Provincial government funds were allocated to Hydro for rural development in the 1920s and moderate growth was maintained until World War II interrupted the rural construction program. After the war, however, rural electrification in southern Ontario progressed rapidly until 1958 when provincial money for that region was substantially reduced and Hydro redirected its attention to the needs of the North. While Fleming shows that the public utility proved responsive to changing economic conditions, technological developments, and political considerations as it became a world leader in rural electrification, he also presents evidence of the policies and methods which have engendered negative sentiment toward Ontario Hydro. For example, he reveals that the "power at cost" policy was both a way to achieve price reduction and a strategy for price maintenance. In describing the various influences on Ontario Hydro's program of rural electrification, Fleming has drawn from an impressive array of archival and newspaper sources, including the Ontario Hydro Archives, the Ontario Archives of the Hydro-Electric Commission, and files in the office of the Ontario Premier. Power at Cost will become the standard reference on the subject of rural electrification in Ontario.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356310040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563100/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 